title: For Sale:  72,659 NICS denials = 62 cases referred for prosecution.
location: Tell Obama to do his job., Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Yes, that's right, in 2010 72,659 attempted firearms transactions were denied by NICS. Of those just 62 were ever even referred for prosecution. When recently asked by NRA representative Jim Baker about the lack of prosecutions for lying on form 4473 Joe Biden responded: "And to your point, Mr. Baker, regarding the lack of prosecutions on lying on Form 4473s, we simply don't have the time or manpower to prosecute everybody who lies on a form, that checks a wrong box, that answers a question inaccurately." 

So, basically, the Obama administration can't be bothered to enforce the laws we already have but wants new laws to burden law abiding gun owners. Tell your senators and rep: No new gun control and that Obama needs to do his job and enforce the laws we already have.

You can write all your senators and reps here. 

http://www.nraila.org/get-involved-locally/grassroots/write-your-reps.aspx

Proposed text follows:


"
I would like to know why we are even considering additional gun control laws when existing federal law is not being enforced? 

In 2010 according to a report entitled:

 "Enforcement of the Brady Act, 2010: Federal and State Investigations and Prosecutions of Firearm Applicants Denied by a NICS Check in 2010",

Which can be found at:

https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/bjs/grants/239272.pdf

there were 72,659 NICS denials. Only 6.2% were even referred to ATF field offices for investigation and of those only 62, yes, that's right 62, not 62% but 62, were ultimately referred by the ATF to federal prosecutors. 

It is against federal law to provide false information on form 4473, which must be completed prior to a NICS check, and the NICS check is not run if an answer is given that indicates an individual is prohibited from receiving a firearm. Based on this, either, NICS is so flawed that out of 72,659 denials only 62 should have denied, or the Obama administration has absolutely no interest in enforcing federal law. I'm betting on the latter since according to the NRA, of which I am a member, when their representative, Jim Baker recently asked why the prosecution rate for lying on form 4473 was so low, Joe Biden Responded:  "And to your point, Mr. Baker, regarding the lack of prosecutions on lying on Form 4473s, we simply don't have the time or manpower to prosecute everybody who lies on a form, that checks a wrong box, that answers a question inaccurately." In other words, the Obama administration, which wants to burden law abiding gun owners with numerous additional gun laws, cannot be bothered to enforce the ones we have now.   Why should we even CONSIDER passing more laws when the administration refuses to enforce those we already have? What's the point? Perhaps if the administration would actually do it's job and enforce existing law there wouldn't even be a perceived need for any more laws. We certainly don't need more laws for both criminals AND the Obama administration to ignore.

 I oppose ALL new gun control laws, and, frankly, think that if Obama and Biden cannot be bothered to do their jobs and see that existing federal law is enforced they should both either step down or be removed from office. 


"

title: For Sale:  S&W 520 NYSP New York State Police Contract .357 Magnum
postcontent:
Absolutely pristine example of a very rare, very collectable revolver.

The Model 520 was commissioned in 1979 by the NYSP as a fixed-sight, N-Frame revolver chambered in .357 magnum.  NYSP backed out of the deal, but S&W had already completed 3000 revolvers, which, in 1980, they distributed for sale to the civilian consumer market.  S&W never made another fixed-sight N-Frame.

This example is in amazing condition, with no turn ring, and a deep, beautiful blue. but without the box.  The price has been adjusted to reflect the missing box, and is firm.

I am not interested in any trades at this time.

postcontent:
For Sale - Walther PP in 7.65mm (.32 ACP). 

Nice blue steel and serial number 366XXX (last three digits not shown for privacy). This is a 1967 manufacture, based on the serial number and barrel as well, as it says "67" on the barrel as well and has the deer antlers and other marks, as to show proofings of being assembled and test fired at Ulm/Do (West Germany at the time and now Germany, having been reunited long ago). Importer is Interarms (Alexandria, VA). 

Fires great, accurate and all. James Bond style all the way. Never had a jam with it either on both European and American made ammo. Magazine holds 8 rounds. 

This gun is NOT on the California roster, thus very rare in California and not easy to find. Being that it's not on the roster, like many other guns, any of these old Walthers cannot be sold by an FFL here in this State or by FFL or private party out of State, so one cannot get one online and have it shipped here, since it's not on the roster. It can only be sold private party within this state. They just keep getting more and more difficult to find here in California, so this is a great chance to get one and a cool piece of history. 

$1,250 or make offer.
